TY  - JOUR
T1  - Long-Range Planning And Organizational Performance: A Cross-Valuation Study
AU  - Herold, David M.
Y1  - 1972/03/01
PY  - 1972
DA  - 1972/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/254803
DO  - 10.5465/254803
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 91
EP  - 102
VL  - 15
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study is an attempt to validate and extend a study by Thune & House on the performance of formal planners vs informal planners. A new independent variable, profits, was used to cross-validate the planning questionnaire of the original study. In addition, it was hypothesized that R & D expenditures would be higher for the formal planners than for the informal planners. This, if confirmed, would provide a second source of construct validity for the original questionnaire due to the future orientation of both formal planning and R & D, which would lead one to be theoretically predicted by the other. Using a sample of five pairs of formal and informal planners, comparison over a 7-year period showed formal planners to outperform informal planners on sales and profits and to significantly out-spend informal planners on R & D expenditures. Theoretical limitations and implications are discussed.
AB  - This study is an attempt to validate and extend a study by Thune & House on the performance of formal planners vs informal planners. A new independent variable, profits, was used to cross-validate the planning questionnaire of the original study. In addition, it was hypothesized that R & D expenditures would be higher for the formal planners than for the informal planners. This, if confirmed, would provide a second source of construct validity for the original questionnaire due to the future orientation of both formal planning and R & D, which would lead one to be theoretically predicted by the other. Using a sample of five pairs of formal and informal planners, comparison over a 7-year period showed formal planners to outperform informal planners on sales and profits and to significantly out-spend informal planners on R & D expenditures. Theoretical limitations and implications are discussed.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/254803
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/254803
Y2  - 2026/04/24
