TY  - JOUR
T1  - Machiavellianism As A Factor In Managerial Job Strain, Job Satisfaction, And Upward Mobility
AU  - Gemmill, Gary R.
AU  - Heisler, W. J.
Y1  - 1972/03/01
PY  - 1972
DA  - 1972/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/254800
DO  - 10.5465/254800
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 51
EP  - 62
VL  - 15
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study investigates the relationship between Machiavellian orientation and several job-related correlates among 150 managers in a large manufacturing firm. The findings indicate that Machiavellian orientation is positively associated with job strain and perceived opportunity for formal control, and negatively associated with job satisfaction. Machiavellian orientation was not significantly associated with upward mobility.
AB  - This study investigates the relationship between Machiavellian orientation and several job-related correlates among 150 managers in a large manufacturing firm. The findings indicate that Machiavellian orientation is positively associated with job strain and perceived opportunity for formal control, and negatively associated with job satisfaction. Machiavellian orientation was not significantly associated with upward mobility.
